Table 3 shows the main results on test sets when using Comet-qe-da or Comet-qe-mqm as the QE-based reward model.
We present the results of UniTE-MUP in Appendix D and use chrF as the evaluation metric in Appendix E.
Table 4 presents the test results when UniTE-MUP functions as the reward model.
The main trends are consistent with those shown in Table 3.
We also observe that neither RAFT nor RAFT+ achieves positive improvement in high-resource language pairs when Nllb-200-1.3B is the base model.
We speculate that this lack of improvement is due to overoptimization problems caused by the presence of errors that are not related to length ratio and off-target errors.

Table 4 presents the test results when UniTE-MUP functions as the reward model.
The main trends are consistent with those shown in Table 3.
We also observe that neither RAFT nor RAFT+ achieves positive improvement in high-resource language pairs when Nllb-200-1.3B is the base model.
We speculate that this lack of improvement is due to overoptimization problems caused by the presence of errors that are not related to length ratio and off-target errors.
